[normal]2[bold].) Those recently granted refugee status.[bold]By the nature of our work, and that of our Committee members, we retain contact with many former asylum seekers who acquired a form of Leave to Remain, be it as  full refugees, or Discr
[normal]etionary (Legacy
[normal]) Leave. They may seek work and accommodation, but in the current climate this is incredibly hard. Many end up as home carers, cleaners  or security staff, employed on zero-hours contracts. We need not spell out the consequences of inadequa
[normal]te and irregular income which engulfs them. Here is 
[normal]a
[normal] case study:
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Francophone recently granted DLR under the Legacy backlog cases, works as an agency  home 
[normal]carer
[normal] at £3.50/ hour 
[normal]excluding
[normal] travel costs, achieving on average 16-20 hours per week, or £112-£120.-
[normal]Lived in a studio flat costing £900.-/ month, only part covered by Housing Benefit. She relies each month on church support for her food and utility bills. She has recently left the f
[normal]lat and moved in with friends , hoping to save enough  to get her 16 year old daughter over here who is at risk of a premature Muslim marriage and female circumcision. 
[normal]It means she no longer meets HO rules for housing her child.
[normal]As this form of  Leave gran
[normal]ted does not permit Family Reunion as a refugee, she will need to earn £18.600+ to qualify for bringing her child to safety, which she will not achieve before the girl’s 18
[normal]th
[normal] birthday.....Paying to challenge the Family Rules  of July 2012, or her working c
[normal]onditions,  is out of the question without Legal Aid.
