[normal]10) P[bold]roviders of legal services in applications for judicial review against public bodies should only be paid for work done on the case if the Court[bold]s[bold] grant[bold] Leave [bold]to proceed[bold].[bold]Much of the preparatory work for a Judicial Review must be performed prior to lodging. 
[normal]This was a result of the reforms following the Carter Review. 
[normal]The advantage of this is less work/ cost post Leave to appeal, and better
[normal] ongoing 
[normal] 
[normal]communication between counsels 
[normal]and their instructing solicitors
[normal], 
[normal] and the courts. 
[normal]Many of the cases presented 
[normal], especially
[normal] but not only, 
[normal] in asylum/ immigration, are of the sort which have life changing consequences if 
[normal] statutory decisions
[normal] are not challenged
[normal].  
[normal]In addition a number of them are prepared
[normal] specifically  to investigate
[normal] significant issues of public inte
[normal]rest which have previously been denied hearing, yet clearly need clarification or challenging as to their legality.
[normal] 
[normal]Should the preparatory work for such issues no longer be payable, then solicitors will no longer be able to instruct and pay counsels witho
[normal]ut putting their firm’
[normal]s economic survival at risk. It will increase the number of appeals against refusals of Leave to Proceed
[normal], another Court burden.
[normal] 
[normal]Furthermore, w
[normal]e are  aware that many of the cases currently submitted for Leave to Proceed to Judicial Re
[normal]view, will result in the respondent 
[normal]‘
[normal]giving way
[normal]’
[normal] and  hence bringing the case to an acceptable outcome without incurring further public costs. The level of such pre-hearing agreements is , we are told and have experienced, very high; ( around 50%, see also
[normal] Armstrong, footnote 8) since lawyers would not usually pursue a matter if they were not already convinced of 
[normal]it
[normal]’
[normal]s
[normal] merit, both in legal terms and in Legal Aid criteria parlance Such cases are de facto ‘successful’ from the point of view of the appellant. However his/her legal team 
[normal]would not be paid
[normal] for that good outcome.  
[normal]We are aware that the intentions of the 
[normal]rece
[normal]nt 
[normal]legislation 
[normal]on the legal profession’s reform, 
[normal]are to 
[normal]significantly 
[normal]shrink the number of 
[normal] public law practitioners
[normal] through
[normal] removing 
[normal] their ability to 
[normal]draw
[normal] upon Legal Aid
[normal]. B
[normal]ut to do so by denying the less affluent, less articulate  members of those in the
[normal] UK  
[normal]a
[normal] legal remedy is unjust
[normal] and 
[normal]discriminatory, 
[normal]contraven
[normal]ing both the Equality Directive on equal access to goods and services and 
[normal] Art.6 of the ECHR
[normal] on the right to fair trial. It will short
[normal] 
[normal]circuit and thus  
[normal] 
[normal]deeply 
[normal]damage the quality of legal debate i
[normal]n our 
[normal]country
[normal] and eventually our legal profession, and it
[normal]’
[normal]s
[normal] 
[normal]deservedly 
[normal]eminent
[normal] global reputation. Both will irreparably damage  the common good.
