[normal]11)[bold] 
[normal]L[bold]egal aid should be removed for all cases assessed as having “borderline” prospects of success.[bold]This section does not differentiate between ‘borderline’ and ‘vexatious’ cases: Legal Aid removal for cases clearly falling into the latter category is of course justifiable....if ‘vexatious ‘ is what they are........However, ‘borderline’, as used here,  i
[normal]s a concept which is seriously deficient in practical application: 
[normal]The LAA Legal Aid awarding authority already implements a self administered assessment by the solicitor, the ‘merits test’. Many solicitors practice it in a very cautious manner
[normal] to avoid lo
[normal]sing income
[normal], sometimes resulting in deserving cases not being heard for lack of Legal Aid (so-called ‘cherry picking’)
[normal].
[normal] 
[normal]Other practitioners, committed to their client
[normal]’s predicament
[normal], will take more risk in assigning ‘merit’ and 
[normal]persist in 
[normal]apply
[normal]ing
[normal] for Lega
[normal]l Aid. But there is an issue he
[normal]re of potential damage to 
[normal]development
[normal] of the law
[normal]:  ‘Borderline’ cases are often those where existing case law or expert evidence is not conclusive or  situation
[normal]s
[normal] in the ‘real world’
[normal]  have
[normal] changed such as to require judicial r
[normal]e-examination.
[normal] 
[normal]On such occasions a ‘borderline’ case will serve the public interest of developing a new judicial consensus to address the
[normal]se
[normal] changed circumstances. 
[normal]Within the immigration- and asylum  field that continues to happen on a regular basis: the 
[normal]resolution of issues around female gender, definitions of persecution, of internal relocation, of freedom to practice  or openly hold religious or political views have all been the subject of such ‘borderline’ cases and resolved in a manner which changes c
[normal]ase law judicial consensus. 
[normal] 
[normal]We do not therefore approve of this proposal to tighten exclusion for cases whose assessment of merit are not immediately clear cut.
